<Document>
<name>Pacific Coast Highway — Big Sur</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Pacific Coast Highway — Big Sur</h2><p><i>California, USA · CA-1, Carmel-by-the-Sea to San Simeon</i></p><p><b>The benchmark coastal drive: 145 km between surf and a wall of redwood-clad Santa Lucias.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>135 km (84 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4 hrs no stops; 6–8 hrs with stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (rockslides and fog can close it any time of year)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Frequent winter closures from rockslides; coastal fog; slow RVs; few gas stations</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>304</td></tr></table><hr><p>This is the prototype against which every other coast highway is measured. The road was hand-cut into the Santa Lucia Mountains during the 1920s and 30s with convict labor and dynamite, opening in 1937. You drive between Pacific surf and a near-vertical wall of redwood, manzanita, and yucca. Henry Miller called Big Sur 'the face of the Earth as the Creator intended it to look.' Driving south is best — your lane is on the cliff side, with the turnouts on your right. Stop often. Fuel up before entering.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Bixby Creek Bridge</b> — Iconic 1932 spandrel-arch bridge — 218 m long, 85 m above the creek. Photo turnouts on both north and south approaches.</li><li><b>Hurricane Point</b> — Highest point on this stretch and the windiest. Pull off for the long view back to Bixby Bridge.</li><li><b>Point Sur Lighthouse</b> — 1889 sandstone tower on a basalt sea-stack; volunteer-led tours weekends Apr–Oct.</li><li><b>Pfeiffer Beach</b> — Hidden cove with purple-tinged sand from manganese garnet washing out of the cliffs. Narrow access road; no RVs.</li><li><b>McWay Falls</b> — 24 m year-round waterfall pouring directly onto a beach — one of only two 'tide falls' in California. Short walk from Julia Pfeiffer Burns SP.</li><li><b>Piedras Blancas elephant seal rookery</b> — 17,000 northern elephant seals year-round; peak December–March (births and bull combat). Free boardwalk.</li><li><b>Hearst Castle (San Simeon)</b> — William Randolph Hearst's hilltop palace — 165 rooms, 127 acres of gardens. Tours by reservation.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
